</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="169" pageNumber="170" type="type">
<paragraph pageId="169" pageNumber="170">Type.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="169" pageNumber="170">
GREECE, Crete, 
<normalizedToken originalValue="IerÃ¡petra">Ierapetra</normalizedToken>
. 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="169" pageNumber="170">Greuter</emphasis>
7802 (holotype Hb. Greuter (B or PAL?); isotypes E00288017!, G, LD, W!).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="169" pageNumber="170" type="distinguishing features">
<paragraph pageId="169" pageNumber="170">Distinguishing features.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="169" pageNumber="170">
Undershrub clearly related to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Desr., Encycl. [Lamarck et al.] 3: 552. 1792. (Desrousseaux" authorityYear="1792" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Convolvulus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Convolvulus oleifolius" order="Solanales" pageId="169" pageNumber="170" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="oleifolius">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="169" pageNumber="170">Convolvulus oleifolius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and distinguished by its unusual habit. It is a pendulous plant, strongly acrotonous in its branching with the leaves in fasciculate bunches. No floral differences from 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Desr., Encycl. [Lamarck et al.] 3: 552. 1792. (Desrousseaux" authorityYear="1792" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Convolvulus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Convolvulus oleifolius" order="Solanales" pageId="169" pageNumber="170" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="oleifolius">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="169" pageNumber="170">Convolvulus oleifolius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are known.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="169" pageNumber="170" type="description">
<paragraph pageId="169" pageNumber="170">Description.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="169" pageNumber="170">Endemic to Crete.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="169" pageNumber="170" type="notes">
<paragraph pageId="169" pageNumber="170">Notes.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="169" pageNumber="170">
It is impossible to confirm whether this is a distinct relict species or some peculiar adaptation of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Desr., Encycl. [Lamarck et al.] 3: 552. 1792. (Desrousseaux" authorityYear="1792" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Convolvulus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Convolvulus oleifolius" order="Solanales" pageId="169" pageNumber="170" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="oleifolius">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="169" pageNumber="170">Convolvulus oleifolius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
to the cliff habitat. Its population is apparently restricted to a small number of plants on one or two limestone cliffs.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
